# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batting-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:batting-baseball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:batting-baseball/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:batting-baseball/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:batting-baseball/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:batting-baseball/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:batting-baseball/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:batting-baseball/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:batting-baseball/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:batting-baseball/alfons-hitter] Hitter surrendered to Soviet forces in 1944 during Operation Bagration when his division was encircled at Vitebsk.
[src:batting-baseball/alfons-hitter] Convicted as a war criminal in the Soviet Union, he was held in prison for eleven years, joining the National Committee for a Free Germany while in captivity.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] An **aluminium alloy** (UK/IUPAC) or **aluminum alloy** (NA; see spelling differences) is an alloy in which aluminium (Al) is the predominant metal.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The typical alloying elements are copper, magnesium, manganese, silicon, tin, nickel and zinc.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] There are two principal classifications, namely casting alloys and wrought alloys, both of which are further subdivided into the categories heat-treatable and non-heat-treatable.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] About 85% of aluminium is used for wrought products, for example rolled plate, foils and extrusions.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Cast aluminium alloys yield cost-effective products due to their low melting points, although they generally have lower tensile strengths than wrought alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The most important cast aluminium alloy system is Al–Si, where the high levels of silicon (4–13%) contribute to give good casting characteristics.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are widely used in engineering structures and components where light weight or corrosion resistance is required.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Alloys composed mostly of aluminium have been very important in aerospace manufacturing since the introduction of metal-skinned aircraft.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium–magnesium alloys are both lighter than other aluminium alloys and much less flammable than other alloys that contain a very high percentage of magnesium.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloy surfaces will develop a white, protective layer of aluminium oxide when left unprotected by anodizing or correct painting procedures.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] In a wet environment, galvanic corrosion can occur when an aluminium alloy is placed in electrical contact with other metals with more positive corrosion potentials than aluminium, and an electrolyte is present that allows ion exchange.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Also referred to as dissimilar-metal corrosion, this process can occur as exfoliation or as intergranular corrosion.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys can be improperly heat-treated, causing internal element separation which corrodes the metal from the inside out.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloy compositions are registered with The Aluminum Association.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Many organizations publish more specific standards for the manufacture of aluminium alloys, including the SAE International standards organization, specifically its aerospace standards subgroups, and ASTM International.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys with a wide range of properties are used in engineering structures.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Alloy systems are classified by a number system (ANSI) or by names indicating their main alloying constituents (DIN and ISO).
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Selecting the right alloy for a given application entails considerations of its tensile strength, density, ductility, formability, workability, weldability, and corrosion resistance, to name a few.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] A brief historical overview of alloys and manufacturing technologies is given in.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are used extensively in aircraft due to their high strength-to-weight ratio.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Pure aluminium is much too soft for such uses, and it does not have the high tensile strength that is needed for building airplanes and helicopters.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys typically have elastic moduli of about 70 GPa, which is about one-third of the elastic modulus of steel alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Therefore, for a given load, a component or unit made of an aluminium alloy will experience a greater deformation in the elastic regime than a steel part of identical size and shape.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] With completely new metal products, the design choices are often governed by the choice of manufacturing technology.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Extrusions are particularly important in this regard, owing to the ease with which aluminium alloys, particularly the Al-Mg-Si series, can be extruded to form complex profiles.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] In general, stiffer and lighter designs can be achieved with aluminium alloys than is feasible with steels.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] For instance, consider the bending of a thin-walled tube: the second moment of area is inversely related to the stress in the tube wall; that is, stresses are lower for larger values.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The second moment of area is proportional to the cube of the radius times the wall thickness, so increasing the radius (and weight) by 26% will lead to a halving of the wall stress.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] For this reason, bicycle frames made of aluminium alloys make use of larger tube diameters than steel or titanium in order to yield the desired stiffness and strength.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] In automotive engineering, cars made of aluminium alloys employ space frames made of extruded profiles to ensure rigidity.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] This represents a radical change from the common approach for current steel car design, which depend on the body shells for stiffness, known as unibody design.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are widely used in automotive engines, particularly in engine blocks and crankcases due to the weight savings that are possible.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Since aluminium alloys are susceptible to warping at elevated temperatures, the cooling system of such an engine is critical.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Manufacturing techniques and metallurgical advancements have also been instrumental for successful applications in automotive engines.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] In the 1960s, the aluminium cylinder heads of the Chevrolet Corvair earned a reputation for failure and stripping of threads, which is not seen in current aluminium cylinder heads.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] An important structural limitation of aluminium alloys is their lower fatigue strength compared to steel.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] In controlled laboratory conditions, steels display a fatigue limit, which is the stress amplitude below which no failures occur – the metal does not continue to weaken with extended stress cycles.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys do not have this lower fatigue limit and will continue to weaken with continued stress cycles.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are therefore sparsely used in parts that require high fatigue strength in the high-cycle regime (more than 107 stress cycles).
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Often, the metal's sensitivity to heat must also be considered.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Even a relatively routine workshop procedure involving heating is complicated by the fact that aluminium, unlike steel, will melt without first glowing red.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Forming operations where a blow torch is used can reverse or remove the effects of heat treatment.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] No visual signs reveal how the material is internally damaged.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Much like welding heat-treated, high-strength link chain, all strength is now lost by heat of the torch.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The chain is dangerous and must be discarded.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium is subject to internal stresses and strains.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Sometimes years later, improperly welded aluminium bicycle frames may gradually twist out of alignment from the stresses of the welding process.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Thus, the aerospace industry avoids heat altogether by joining parts with rivets of like-metal composition, other fasteners, or adhesives.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Stresses in overheated aluminium can be relieved by heat-treating the part in an oven and gradually cooling it—in effect annealing the stresses.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Yet these parts may still become distorted, so that heat-treating of welded bicycle frames, for instance, can result in a significant fraction becoming misaligned.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] If the misalignment is not too severe, the cooled parts may be bent into alignment.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] If the frame is properly designed for rigidity (see above), that bending will require enormous force.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium's intolerance of high temperatures has not precluded its use in rocketry, even for use in constructing combustion chambers where gases can reach 3500 K.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Because of its high conductivity and relatively low price compared with copper in the 1960s, aluminium was introduced at that time for household electrical wiring in North America, even though many fixtures had not been designed to accept aluminium wire.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] All of this resulted in overheated and loose connections, and this in turn resulted in some fires.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Builders then became wary of using the wire, and many jurisdictions outlawed its use in very small sizes, in new construction.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Yet newer fixtures were eventually introduced with connections designed to avoid loosening and overheating.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] At first they were marked "Al/Cu", but they now bear a "CO/ALR" coding.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Another way to forestall the heating problem is to crimp the short "pigtail" of copper wire.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] A properly done high-pressure crimp by the proper tool is tight enough to reduce any thermal expansion of the aluminium.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Today, new alloys, designs, and methods are used for aluminium wiring in combination with aluminium terminations.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Wrought and cast aluminium alloys use different identification systems.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Wrought aluminium is identified with a four-digit number which identifies the alloying elements.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Cast aluminium alloys use a four-to-five-digit number with a decimal point.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The digit in the hundreds place indicates the alloying elements, while the digit after the decimal point indicates the form (cast shape or ingot).
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The temper designation follows the cast or wrought designation number with a dash, a letter, and potentially a one-to-three-digit number, e.g.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Note: -W is a relatively soft intermediary designation that applies after heat treat and before aging is completed.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The -W condition can be extended at extremely low temperatures but not indefinitely and depending on the material will typically last no longer than 15 minutes at ambient temperatures.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The International Alloy Designation System is the most widely accepted naming scheme for wrought alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Each alloy is given a four-digit number, where the first digit indicates the major alloying elements, the second—if different from 0—indicates a variation of the alloy, and the third and fourth digits identify the specific alloy in the series.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] For example, in alloy 3105, the number 3 indicates the alloy is in the manganese series, 1 indicates the first modification of alloy 3005, and finally 05 identifies it in the 3000 series.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 1000 series are essentially pure aluminium with a minimum 99% aluminium content by weight and can be work hardened.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 2000 series alloys are alloyed with copper and can be precipitation hardened to strengths comparable to steel.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Formerly referred to as duralumin, they were once the most common aerospace alloys, but were susceptible to stress corrosion cracking and are increasingly replaced by 7000 series alloys in new designs.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 3000 series alloys are alloyed with manganese, and can be work hardened.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 4000 series alloys are alloyed with silicon.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Variations of aluminium–silicon alloys intended for casting (and therefore not included in 4000 series) are also known as silumin.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 5000 series alloys are alloyed with magnesium, and offer superb corrosion resistance, making them suitable for marine applications.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 5083 alloy has the highest strength of non-heat-treated alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Most 5000 series alloys include manganese as well.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 6000 series alloys are alloyed with magnesium and silicon.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] They are easy to machine, are weldable, and can be precipitation hardened, but not to the high strengths that 2000 and 7000 can reach.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 6061 alloy is one of the most commonly used general-purpose aluminium alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 7000 series alloys are alloyed with zinc, and can be precipitation hardened to the highest strengths of any aluminium alloy.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Most 7000 series alloys include magnesium and copper as well.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 8000 series alloys are alloyed with other elements which are not covered by other series.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium–lithium alloys are an example.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Manganese plus chromium must be between 0.12 and 0.50%.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] This limit applies to all elements for which no other limit is specified on a given row, because no column exists or because the column is blank.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The Aluminum Association (AA) has adopted a nomenclature similar to that of wrought alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] British Standard and DIN have different designations.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] In the AA system, the second two digits reveal the minimum percentage of aluminium; for example, 150.x corresponds to a minimum of 99.50% aluminium.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The digit after the decimal point takes a value of 0 or 1, denoting casting and ingot respectively.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Titanium alloys, which are stronger but heavier than Al-Sc alloys, are still much more widely used.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The main application of metallic scandium by weight is in aluminium–scandium alloys for minor aerospace industry components.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] These alloys contain between 0.1% and 0.5% (by weight) of scandium.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] They were used in the Russian military aircraft MiG-21 and MiG-29.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Some items of sports equipment, which rely on high-performance materials, have been made with scandium–aluminium alloys, including baseball bats, lacrosse sticks, bicycle frames and components, and tent poles.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] U.S. gunmaker Smith & Wesson produces revolvers with frames composed of scandium alloy and cylinders of titanium.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Due to its light weight and high strength, aluminium alloys are desired materials to be applied in spacecraft, satellites, and other components to be deployed in space.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] However, this application is limited by the energetic particle irradiation emitted by the Sun.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The impact and deposition of solar energetic particles within the microstructure of conventional aluminium alloys can induce the dissolution of most common hardening phases, leading to softening.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The recently introduced crossover aluminium alloys are being tested as surrogates to 6xxx and 7xxx series alloys in environments where energetic particle irradiation is a major concern.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Such crossover aluminium alloys can be hardened via precipitation of a chemical complex phase known as T-phase in which the radiation resistance has been proved to be superior than other hardening phases of conventional aluminium alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The terms **aircraft aluminium** or **aerospace aluminium** usually refers to 7075.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 4047 aluminium is a unique alloy used in aerospace and automotive applications as a cladding alloy or filler material.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] As filler, aluminium alloy 4047 strips can be combined to intricate applications to bond two metals.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 6951 is a heat-treatable alloy providing additional strength to the fins while increasing sag resistance; this allows the manufacturer to reduce the gauge of the sheet and therefore reducing the weight of the formed fin.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] These distinctive features make aluminium alloy 6951 one of the preferred alloys for heat transfer and heat exchangers manufactured for aerospace applications.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 6063 aluminium alloys are heat-treatable with moderately high strength, excellent corrosion resistance, and good extrudability.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] They are regularly used as architectural and structural members.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] These alloys are used for boat building and shipbuilding, and other marine and salt-water sensitive shore applications.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 4043, 5183, 6005A, and 6082 also used in marine constructions and off shore applications.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 6111 aluminium and 2008 aluminium are extensively used for external automotive body panels, with 5083 and 5754 used for inner body panels.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Bonnets have been manufactured from 2036, 6016, and 6111 alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Truck and trailer body panels have used 5456 aluminium.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Automobile frames often use 5182 aluminium or 5754 aluminium formed sheets, 6061 or 6063 extrusions.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Wheels have been cast from A356.0 aluminium or formed 5xxx sheet.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Engine blocks and crankcases are often cast from aluminium alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] The most popular aluminium alloys used for cylinder blocks are A356, 319, and to a minor extent 242.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys containing cerium are being developed and implemented in high-temperature automotive applications, such as cylinder heads and turbochargers, and in other energy-generation applications.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] These alloys were initially developed as a way to increase the usage of cerium, which is over-produced in rare-earth mining operations for more coveted elements such as neodymium and dysprosium, but gained attention for their strength at high temperatures over long periods of time.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] They gain strength from the presence of an Al11Ce3 intermetallic phase which is stable up to temperatures of 540 °C, and retains its strength up to 300 °C, making it quite viable at elevated temperatures.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium–cerium alloys are typically cast, due to their excellent casting properties, although work has also been done to show that laser-based additive manufacturing techniques can be used as well to create parts with more complex geometries and greater mechanical properties.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] Recent work has largely focused on adding higher-order alloying elements to the binary Al-Ce system to improve its mechanical performance at room and elevated temperatures, such as iron, nickel, magnesium, or copper, and work is being done to understand the alloying element interactions further.
[src:batting-baseball/aluminium-alloy] 6061 aluminium and 6351 aluminium are widely used in breathing gas cylinders for scuba diving and SCBA alloys.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:batting-baseball/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] In baseball, an **appeal play** occurs when a member of the defensive team calls the attention of an umpire to an infraction that they would otherwise ignore.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] To properly execute a live ball appeal, a fielder must, with a live ball, tag the runner or base in question and communicate to the umpire what the infraction was and which runner committed the infraction.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Such communication may be non-verbal, implicit, or assumed—so long as the intent of the fielder is clear to the umpire.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Contrary to popular belief, an appeal out is not a force out unless it is regarding a missed force base.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] For example, if a runner from third base tags up and scores, but a runner from second base leaves too early, failing to tag up, and then is put out on the appeal, the run counts if it was scored before the appeal by the fielders.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Rare situations with a viable appeal on a runner who misses his force base require the umpire to recognize an apparent fourth out.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Umpires will only rule on legal appeals.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] A potential appeal is *viable* if the appeal is legal and the umpire knows that the runner has indeed committed an infraction and will be called out if the appeal is executed by a fielder.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Suppose that runners are on first and third base, and the batter hits a fly ball.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The runner on third tags up, leaving third base immediately after the outfielder touches the ball.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The runner seems to score, beating the throw home, but failing to touch home plate.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The runner proceeds into his dugout without again attempting to touch home base.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The runner on first base stays at first base, and action becomes relaxed while the ball is in the infield.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The fielders now suspect that the runner left third base too early and also missed the plate.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Suppose then that a fielder, with the live ball, touches home base and says to the nearest umpire, "I think they never touched home." This is a legal and viable appeal, and so the umpire should call the runner out and direct that his run shall not count.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Since the ball was live (and indeed must be for appeals to be legal), the runner from first could have attempted to advance at any time during the appeals.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] If the defense attempts to play on that runner, their opportunity to appeal the runner from third base is lost, and the run would count regardless of any subsequent attempt to appeal.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] A member of the defensive team may appeal to the umpire when a batter bats out of turn.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The umpire then enforces the penalty for batting out of turn, if any.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The ball must be live for this as for any appeal.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] After the appeal is made, the umpire will usually signal "Time" and figure out whether the appeal is successful.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The field umpire then signals whether the batter swung, and such a judgment must, by rule, prevail.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The umpire asked is usually the first-base umpire (or third-base, if the batter is left-handed).
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] The plate umpire is not required to ask for assistance if they believe the request is making a farce of the game.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] If the bat barely left the shoulder of the batter and the catcher appeals the "no-swing" call, the umpire will probably deny the appeal.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] This procedure was introduced because it is commonplace for a plate umpire to be unable to see some swings.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] A manager may ask an umpire to request assistance on other plays where another umpire had a better view, but the umpire is not required to do so.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] Such requests are common when a close home run or foul ball call is disputed, or when determining the accuracy of a close catch or no catch call.
[src:batting-baseball/appeal-play] In such a case, the plate umpire would put a new ball in play, and after the ball became live by rule, the defense could appeal the missed base.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:batting-baseball/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] In baseball, **batting** is the act of facing the opposing pitcher and trying to produce offense for one's team.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] A **batter** or **hitter** is a person whose turn it is to face the pitcher.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The three main goals of batters are to become a baserunner, to drive runners home or to advance runners along the bases for others to drive home, but the techniques and strategies they use to do so vary.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Hitting uses a motion which is virtually unique to baseball and its fellow bat-and-ball sports, one that is rarely used in other sports.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Hitting is unique because it involves rotating in the horizontal plane of movement, unlike most sports movements which occur in the vertical plane.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] However, their primary objective is to avoid making an out, and helping their team score runs.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] There are several ways they can help their team score runs.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] They may draw a walk if they receive and do not swing the bat at four pitches located outside the strike zone.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] In cases when there is a runner on third and fewer than two outs, they can attempt to hit a sacrifice fly to drive the runner in by allowing the runner on third to tag up and score.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] When there are fewer than two outs and runners on base, they can try to sacrifice bunt to advance the runner(s) or, with a runner on first or with runners on first and third, they can try a hit and run play, also designed to advance the runner(s).
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] They might even be hit by a pitch, reach on an error or—if first is empty or there are two outs—on a dropped third strike.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The defense attempts to get the batter out.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The pitcher's main role in this is to throw the ball in such a way that the batter either strikes out or cannot hit it cleanly so the defense can get him out.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Batting is often cited as one of the most difficult feats in sports because it consists of hitting a small round ball, usually moving at high velocity, with a thin round bat.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Batters getting a hit in three out of ten at bats, giving him a batting average of .300 (pronounced "three hundred") are considered a successful hitter.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] In Major League Baseball, no batter has had over a .400 average at the end of the season since Ted Williams' .406 in 1941, and no batter has ever hit over .367 in a lifetime—Ty Cobb hit .3664.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] An OPS at or near 1.000 is considered to be the mark of an exceptional hitter.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] A sustained OPS at or above 1.000 over a career is a feat only a few hitters have ever been able to reach.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Batters vary in their approach at the plate.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Some are aggressive hitters, usually swinging at the first pitch (as pitchers often attempt to throw a first-pitch strike).
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Others are patient, attempting to work the pitch count in order to observe all the types of pitches a pitcher will use, as well as tire out the pitcher by forcing him to throw many pitches early.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Generally, contact hitters are more aggressive, swinging at pitches within the strike zone, whereas power hitters will lay off borderline strikes in order to get a pitch they can drive for extra bases.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] In preparation of hitting, every baseball player has their own particular warm-up routine.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Warming up before the game is usually done as a team, at the amateur level, and focuses on helping the hitter get in the correct mindset to hit the ball.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The most notable drill used is the "Tee Drill", where batters hit a ball off a baseball tee and correct any issues they found during previous games or practices.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] There are also various hitting devices used during warm-up in the "on deck circle" to try to increase the batter's bat velocity.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The over weighted supplemental devices include swinging multiple bats, standard 23 oz softball bat, heavier 26 oz softball bat, lighter 18 oz softball bat and doughnut ring (16 oz).
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Weighted warm-up devices are commonly used because players feel that warming-up with heavier bats will help them increase bat velocity.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] After the warm-up with a heavier bat, the normal bat seems lighter and players feel they can swing it faster.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The effect of these devices is not only mental, but it may also be physical.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Heavy warm-up loads stimulate the neural system, allowing for increased muscle activation during lighter bat swings.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The use of weighted bats is based on the theory of complex training where sets of heavier and lighter resistances are alternated to increase muscle performance.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] This theory revolves around the idea that muscle contractions are stronger after reaching near maximal contractions.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The postactivation potentiation improves motor neuron pool excitability and increases the number of recruited motor units, both leading to greater power output.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The additional weight may also help strengthen the muscles of the forearms and wrist thus increasing bat velocity, though some evidence suggests that the effect is psychological rather than biomechanical.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The **lineup** or **batting order** is a list of the nine baseball players for a team in the order they will bat.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] During the game, the only way to change the lineup is via substitution, as batting out of turn is not allowed.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Once the ninth person in the lineup finishes batting, the first person bats again; this is the *top of the order*.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Lineups are designed to facilitate manufacturing runs.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Depending on batters' skills, they might be placed in different parts of the lineup.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Of course, when it comes down to it, all batters are attempting to create runs for the team.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The player currently batting in a game is said to be *at the plate*, *at bat*, or *up to bat* (shortened to *up*).
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] To keep the game moving at an orderly pace, the next batter due up waits to take his turn in a circle (actually marked or imaginary) between his team's *dugout* or bench and the batter's box, and is said to be *on deck*, with the circle known as the *on deck circle*.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The player in the batting order after the on deck batter is said to be *in the hole*.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] When baseball was in its beginning years, players made their own bats.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] This allowed players to experiment with different shapes and sizes of the bats.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] It did not take long for players to realize that the best bats were those with rounded barrels.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Wooden bats are rare at most levels other than the pros.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The majority of wooden baseball bats today are made from northern white ash harvested from Pennsylvania or New York.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] White ash is used because of its hardness, durability, strength, weight and feel.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Trees that provide the lumber for baseball bats are often 50 years old, and of all the lumber harvested, the top 10 percent is saved for pro bats.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Recent technology in drying wood has created bats with lower moisture content, which are light enough to make effective baseball bats.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Maple bats cost more than white ash, but they often last longer as a result of their high strength.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] In addition to the Louisville Slugger, there are many other types of bats that have been used throughout the history of baseball.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The introduction of aluminum baseball bats in the 1970s forever changed the game of baseball at every level but the professional.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Aluminum bats are lighter and stronger than wooden bats.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] Due to the trampoline effect that occurs when a baseball hits an aluminum bat, they can hit a ball significantly further than wooden bats can.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] In light of the increase in power of composite and alloy bats, the NCAA and NFHS have adopted more stringent standards regarding the use of composite and alloy bats.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The new BBCOR (Bat-Ball Coefficient of Restitution) standard brought the flexibility of composite and alloy bats more in line with their wooden counterparts, reducing the trampoline effect.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The NCAA changed standards at the start of the 2011 season, and NFHS adopted the same standard for the 2012 baseball season.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] The design of bats also continues to evolve as manufacturers search for ways to magnify the trampoline effect and increase the size of the bat's “sweet spot.” In aluminum bats, a double-walled bat was introduced in the late 1990s.
[src:batting-baseball/batting-baseball] This design comprises an outer wall of scandium-aluminum, an inner wall of a composite material, and a “filling of rubber or a thick fluid between the two walls.
